1093  SPEAKER_SIDE_LEFT | SPEAKER_SIDE_RIGHT)

1096 // similarly obsolete but are unchanged for compatibility reasons).

2058 
2059 //
2060 // This entire set of MPEG Standard/Dialect Guids are obsolete. Do not use them.
2061 //
2062 //====================================================================================================
2063 //====================================================================================================
2064 // The following official MPEG Formats, Subtypes and Specifiers are listed as required or optional
2065 // These official MPEG GUIDs are the preferred method of supporting MPEG/AC-3 media types in new code.
2066 // Older MPEG GUIDs should also be supported for compatibilty, but these new modes are still required.
2067 //====================================================================================================
2068 //====================================================================================================
2069 
2070 /*
2071 This is a summary of what media types/specifiers will be required for all DVD+DSS+DVB+DTV MPEG decoders.
2072 These media types are what the decoder driver must accept, hardware support for all of these media types
2073 may or may not actually be provided by the decoder natively. These media types are intended to define
2074 the "officially" supported MPEG/AC-3 media types that all WHQL certified decoders must implement. This
2075 specifically includes driver and/or hardware support for all the required standards and dialects.
2076 
2077 All MPEG video decoders must support all of the MPEG video modes shown as [required] below.
2078 All MPEG audio decoders must support all of the MPEG audio modes shown as [required] below.
2079 All AC-3 audio decoders must support all of the AC-3 audio modes shown as [required] below.
2080 The line items shown as [optional] need not be implemented, but are possible formats that might be implemented.
2081 
2082 Note that the input/output pin formats are defined by 2 or 3 GUIDs: TYPE, SUBTYPE, and maybe SPECIFIER.
2083 The specifiers are included if the data format is a "dialect" that needs to be differentiated during decoding.
2084 The decoder MUST be prepared to deal with ALL requests for _required_ "Standard" formats OR _required_ "Dialects".
2085 
2086 STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_TYPE_STANDARD_ELEMENTARY_STREAM [required]
2087  STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_SUBTYPE_STANDARD_MPEG1_VIDEO [required]
2088  STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_SPECIFIER_DIALECT_MPEG1_VIDEO [optional]
2089  STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_SUBTYPE_STANDARD_MPEG1_AUDIO [required]
2090  STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_SPECIFIER_DIALECT_MPEG1_AUDIO [optional]
2091  STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_SUBTYPE_STANDARD_MPEG2_VIDEO [required]
2092  STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_SPECIFIER_DIALECT_MPEG2_VIDEO [required]
2093  STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_SUBTYPE_STANDARD_MPEG2_AUDIO [required]
2094  STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_SPECIFIER_DIALECT_MPEG2_AUDIO [optional]
2095  STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_SUBTYPE_STANDARD_AC3_AUDIO [required]
2096  STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_SPECIFIER_DIALECT_AC3_AUDIO [optional]
2097 STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_TYPE_STANDARD_PES_PACKET [required]
2098  STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_SUBTYPE_STANDARD_MPEG1_VIDEO [optional]
2099  STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_SPECIFIER_DIALECT_MPEG1_VIDEO [optional]
2100  STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_SUBTYPE_STANDARD_MPEG1_AUDIO [optional]
2101  STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_SPECIFIER_DIALECT_MPEG1_AUDIO [optional]
2102  STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_SUBTYPE_STANDARD_MPEG2_VIDEO [required]
2103  STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_SPECIFIER_DIALECT_MPEG2_VIDEO [required]
2104  STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_SUBTYPE_STANDARD_MPEG2_AUDIO [required]
2105  STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_SPECIFIER_DIALECT_MPEG2_AUDIO [required]
2106  STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_SUBTYPE_STANDARD_AC3_AUDIO [required]
2107  STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_SPECIFIER_DIALECT_AC3_AUDIO [optional]
2108 STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_TYPE_STANDARD_PACK_HEADER [required]
2109  STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_SUBTYPE_STANDARD_MPEG2_VIDEO [required]
2110  STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_SPECIFIER_DIALECT_MPEG2_VIDEO [required]
2111  STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_SUBTYPE_STANDARD_MPEG2_AUDIO [required]
2112  STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_SPECIFIER_DIALECT_MPEG2_AUDIO [optional]
2113  STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_SUBTYPE_STANDARD_AC3_AUDIO [required]
2114  STATIC_KSDATAFORMAT_SPECIFIER_DIALECT_AC3_AUDIO [optional]
2115 
2116 Note that the SPECIFIER GUIDs normally identify particular versions of MPEG such as DSS and DVD.
2117 This approach was taken to minimize the number of DSS/DVB/DVD/DTV etc. media SUBTYPES.
2118 These specifiers are currently required to disambiguate MPEG syntax _parsing_ by the decoder
2119 using alternate parsing routines or downloadable firmware or hardware decode settings.
2120 
2121 In the future these specifiers will be extended to cover new KS MPEG flavors such as DVB and DTV.
2122 Thus, the optional specifiers will be subject to clarification and/or definition as they are needed.
2123 
2124 Important note: Per the ITU MPEG specs, MPEG 2 media may contain pure MPEG 1 syntax and
2125 any "MPEG 2" PES packets may actually contain MPEG 1 payloads and MPEG 1 syntax. Some MPEG
2126 broadcasts can revert from MPEG2 to MPEG1 format data at their discretion, without warning.
2127 
2128 CAUTION: Decoders MUST attempt to process MPEG data AS SOON AS POSSIBLE after reception.
2129 In particular, elementary MPEG or MPEG PES packet streams should not be aggregated into DVD
2130 "pack headers" internally before submission to the codec hardware if AT ALL POSSIBLE. The
2131 reason is that mpeg data may need to be processed immediately but there may be no additional
2132 MPEG data forthcoming to fill up the PES packet OR DVD "pack" in a timely fashion. This is
2133 particularly true of MPEG dialects that utilize "repeat field signally" to reuse the last
2134 decoded MPEG video field.
2135 
2136 */
2137

2769 /* constants for palettes */
2770 #define KS_iPALETTE_COLORS 256 // Maximum colours in palette
2771 #define KS_iEGA_COLORS 16 // Number colours in EGA palette
2772 #define KS_iMASK_COLORS 3 // Maximum three components
2773 #define KS_iTRUECOLOR 16 // Minimum true colour device
2774 #define KS_iRED 0 // Index position for RED mask
2775 #define KS_iGREEN 1 // Index position for GREEN mask
2776 #define KS_iBLUE 2 // Index position for BLUE mask

2809 typedef LONGLONG REFERENCE_TIME;
2810 
2811 // The BITMAPINFOHEADER contains all the details about the video stream such
2812 // as the actual image dimensions and their pixel depth. A source filter may
2813 // also request that the sink take only a section of the video by providing a
2814 // clipping rectangle in rcSource. In the worst case where the sink filter
2815 // forgets to check this on connection it will simply render the whole thing
2816 // which isn't a disaster. Ideally a sink filter will check the rcSource and
2817 // if it doesn't support image extraction and the rectangle is not empty then
2818 // it will reject the connection. A filter should use SetRectEmpty to reset a
2819 // rectangle to all zeroes (and IsRectEmpty to later check the rectangle).
2820 // The rcTarget specifies the destination rectangle for the video, for most
2821 // source filters they will set this to all zeroes, a downstream filter may
2822 // request that the video be placed in a particular area of the buffers it
2823 // supplies in which case it will call QueryAccept with a non empty target
2824 
2825 typedef struct tagKS_VIDEOINFOHEADER {
2826 
2827  RECT rcSource; // The bit we really want to use
2828  RECT rcTarget; // Where the video should go
2829  DWORD dwBitRate; // Approximate bit data rate
2830  DWORD dwBitErrorRate; // Bit error rate for this stream
2831  REFERENCE_TIME AvgTimePerFrame; // Average time per frame (100ns units)
2832 
2833  KS_BITMAPINFOHEADER bmiHeader;
2834 
2835 } KS_VIDEOINFOHEADER, *PKS_VIDEOINFOHEADER;

3294 // These KS_CC_SUBSTREAM_* bitmasks are used with VBICODECFILTERING_CC_SUBSTREAMS

3296 #define KS_CC_SUBSTREAM_EVEN 0x0002L // Unfiltered Field 2 Data
3297 
3298 // The following flags describe CC field 1 substreams: CC1,CC2,TT1,TT2
3299 #define KS_CC_SUBSTREAM_FIELD1_MASK 0x00F0L
3300 #define KS_CC_SUBSTREAM_SERVICE_CC1 0x0010L
3301 #define KS_CC_SUBSTREAM_SERVICE_CC2 0x0020L
3302 #define KS_CC_SUBSTREAM_SERVICE_T1 0x0040L
3303 #define KS_CC_SUBSTREAM_SERVICE_T2 0x0080L
3304 
3305 // The following flags describe CC field 2 substreams: CC3,CC4,TT3,TT4,XDS
3306 #define KS_CC_SUBSTREAM_FIELD2_MASK 0x1F00L
3307 #define KS_CC_SUBSTREAM_SERVICE_CC3 0x0100L
3308 #define KS_CC_SUBSTREAM_SERVICE_CC4 0x0200L
3309 #define KS_CC_SUBSTREAM_SERVICE_T3 0x0400L
3310 #define KS_CC_SUBSTREAM_SERVICE_T4 0x0800L
3311 #define KS_CC_SUBSTREAM_SERVICE_XDS 0x1000L

3380 typedef struct _VBICODECFILTERING_STATISTICS_COMMON {
3381  DWORD InputSRBsProcessed; // upstream SRBs received
3382  DWORD OutputSRBsProcessed; // downstream SRBs sent
3383  DWORD SRBsIgnored; // SRBs ignored due to no requests
3384  DWORD InputSRBsMissing; // SRBs dropped upstream
3385  DWORD OutputSRBsMissing; // Output dropped because no SRB pending
3386  DWORD OutputFailures; // dropped because of other failure
3387  DWORD InternalErrors; // could not process due to int. failure
3388  DWORD ExternalErrors; // could not process due to ext. failure
3389  DWORD InputDiscontinuities; // discontinuities received
3390  DWORD DSPFailures; // DSP confidence failure
3391  DWORD TvTunerChanges; // number of received KS_TVTUNER_CHANGE_BEGIN_TUNE and KS_TVTUNER_CHANGE_END_TUNE pairs.
3392  DWORD VBIHeaderChanges; // number of received KS_VBI_FLAG_VBIINFOHEADER_CHANGE
3393  DWORD LineConfidenceAvg; // Average of all DSP confidence results
3394  DWORD BytesOutput; // Bytes sent downstream
3395 } VBICODECFILTERING_STATISTICS_COMMON, *PVBICODECFILTERING_STATISTICS_COMMON;
3396 
3397 typedef struct _VBICODECFILTERING_STATISTICS_COMMON_PIN {
3398  DWORD SRBsProcessed; // SRBs sent/received
3399  DWORD SRBsIgnored; // SRBs ignored due to filtering
3400  DWORD SRBsMissing; // SRBs not sent/received
3401  DWORD InternalErrors; // could not send/receive due to int. failure
3402  DWORD ExternalErrors; // could not send/receive due to ext. failure
3403  DWORD Discontinuities; // discontinuities received/sent
3404  DWORD LineConfidenceAvg; // Average of all DSP confidence results for this pin
3405  DWORD BytesOutput; // Bytes sent downstream
3406 } VBICODECFILTERING_STATISTICS_COMMON_PIN, *PVBICODECFILTERING_STATISTICS_COMMON_PIN;

3597 //===========================================================================
3598 // KSSTREAM_HEADER extensions for digital video
3599 //===========================================================================
3600 
3601 #define KS_VIDEO_FLAG_FRAME 0x0000L // Frame or Field (default is frame)
3602 #define KS_VIDEO_FLAG_FIELD1 0x0001L
3603 #define KS_VIDEO_FLAG_FIELD2 0x0002L
3604 
3605 #define KS_VIDEO_FLAG_I_FRAME 0x0000L // I, B, or P (default is I)
3606 #define KS_VIDEO_FLAG_P_FRAME 0x0010L
3607 #define KS_VIDEO_FLAG_B_FRAME 0x0020L
3608 
3609 typedef struct tagKS_FRAME_INFO {
3610  ULONG ExtendedHeaderSize; // Size of this extended header
3611  DWORD dwFrameFlags; // Field1, Field2, or Frame
3612  LONGLONG PictureNumber;
3613  LONGLONG DropCount;
3614 
3615  // The following are only set when using OverlayMixer
3616  HANDLE hDirectDraw; // user mode DDraw handle
3617  HANDLE hSurfaceHandle; // user mode surface handle
3618  RECT DirectDrawRect; // portion of surface locked
3619  // Reserved fields, never reference these
3620  DWORD Reserved1;
3621  DWORD Reserved2;
3622  DWORD Reserved3;
3623  DWORD Reserved4;
3624 } KS_FRAME_INFO, *PKS_FRAME_INFO;

3847 // Describes how the device tunes. Only one of these flags may be set
3848 // in KSPROPERTY_TUNER_MODE_CAPS_S.Strategy
3849 
3850 // Describe how the driver should attempt to tune:
3851 // EXACT: just go to the frequency specified (no fine tuning)
3852 // FINE: (slow) do an exhaustive search for the best signal
3853 // COARSE: (fast) use larger frequency jumps to just determine if any signal
3854 
3855 typedef enum {
3856  KS_TUNER_TUNING_EXACT = 1, // No fine tuning
3857  KS_TUNER_TUNING_FINE, // Fine grained search
3858  KS_TUNER_TUNING_COARSE, // Coarse search
3859 }KS_TUNER_TUNING_FLAGS;
3860 
3861 typedef enum {
3862  KS_TUNER_STRATEGY_PLL = 0X01, // Tune by PLL offset
3863  KS_TUNER_STRATEGY_SIGNAL_STRENGTH = 0X02, // Tune by signal strength
3864  KS_TUNER_STRATEGY_DRIVER_TUNES = 0X04, // Driver does fine tuning
3865 }KS_TUNER_STRATEGY;

5042 } KS_AM_PROPERTY_TS_RATE_CHANGE;
5043 
5044 typedef struct {
5045  // this is the simplest mechanism to set a time stamp rate change on
5046  // a filter (simplest for the person setting the rate change, harder
5047  // for the filter doing the rate change).
5048  REFERENCE_TIME StartTime; //stream time at which to start this rate
5049  LONG Rate; //new rate * 10000 (decimal)
5050 } KS_AM_SimpleRateChange, *PKS_AM_SimpleRateChange;
5051 
5052 typedef struct {
5053  REFERENCE_TIME OutputZeroTime; //input TS that maps to zero output TS
5054  LONG Rate; //new rate * 10000 (decimal)
5055 } KS_AM_ExactRateChange, *PKS_AM_ExactRateChange;

5130 #ifndef __ENCODER_API_DEFINES__
5131 #define __ENCODER_API_DEFINES__
5132 
5133 typedef enum {
5134 
5135  //
5136  // Bit rate used for encoding is constant
5137  //
5138  ConstantBitRate = 0,
5139 
5140  //
5141  // Bit rate used for encoding is variable with the specified bitrate used
5142  // as a guaranteed average over a specified window. The default window
5143  // size is considered to be 5 minutes.
5144  //
5145  VariableBitRateAverage,
5146 
5147  //
5148  // Bit rate used for encoding is variable with the specified bitrate used
5149  // as an average with a peak not to exceed the specified peak bitrate over
5150  // a specified window. The default window size is considered to be 500ms
5151  // (classically one GOP).
5152  //
5153  VariableBitRatePeak
5154 
5155 } VIDEOENCODER_BITRATE_MODE;
5156 
5157 #endif // __ENCODER_API_DEFINES__
